<DOC><DOCNO> AP890324-0175 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2003EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-BRF--PoliceLights     03-24 0181</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Police Lights,0184</SECOND><HEAD>Woman Raped After Stopping For Fake Police Lights</HEAD><DATELINE>WESTERLY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A woman who pulled her car over when shesaw a blue light flashing behind her thought she was being stoppedby police, but instead was overpowered and raped by the driver ofan unmarked car, police said.   Such blue lights cost $6.99 at auto supply stores, police saidthis week. It is not illegal to buy them, although their use isillegal, they said.   The woman told police she was driving near the Connecticutborder Saturday night when a car behind her flashed its high beams,then turned on a flashing blue light.   When she stopped, a man in civilian clothes approached the car,talked with her, then overpowered and handcuffed her before takingher to an isolated stretch of road in Connecticut where she wassexually assaulted, the victim told police.   Eugene C. Texter III, 27, has been charged with kidnapping andfor violating the terms of his bail on a previous sexual assaultcharge. Connecticut State Police were investigating the rape charge.</TEXT></DOC>